ame from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Alice Pembridge was born in 1284, in Castle-Pulverbatch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard de Pembridge, was 21 and her mother, Mrs. Richard de Pembridge, was 21. She married Sir John De Burley in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1395, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 111."},"et":{"1284–1395":"1284–1395","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1305–1383":"1305–1383","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1305":"1305","1264":"1264","1